4755,IssuesEvent,2017-04-14 14:27:58+00:00,17410607,GeospatialPython/pyshp,6413369,karimbahgat,,,closed,Add encoding='' kwarg to shapefile.Reader and shapefile.Writer,[],[],8,"The natural earth data stores its strings encoded as Windows-1252 (versions < 3.x) or UTF-8 (>= 3.x). Currently, shapefile.py tries to guess at what it should do in the b() and u() routines.  For Python-3, utf-8 is assumed as the encoding, and for python-2, no encode or decode operations are performed.

It's my opinion that the user should be able to specify the encoding for the DBF fields as a kwarg to Reader and Writer.  If provided, b() should use that instead of utf-8 for the v.encode() operation, and it should do so for both python 2 and python 3.  Likewise, u(v) should be modified to decode in a similar manner.

This would enable cartopy (a popular mapping module with built-in support for natural earth data) to provide the encoding parameter, returning ""accurate"" data to the user, regardless of natural earth data version or python version.
",{},{}
4819,IssuesEvent,2015-10-05 19:10:29+00:00,31923856,elky/django-flat-theme,60035,andybak,,,opened,Some way for 3rd party apps to target flat theme via CSS,[],[],0,"I've got an admin extension that needs it's CSS tweaked for flat.

So my selector is:

    .selective-inline-item .inline-related 

I'd like to vary it but only for sites using the flat theme. I can think of various hacky workarounds but the nicest thing would be a class on the admin body so that any 3rd party app can have flat theme specific rules:

body.flatadmin .selective-inline-item .inline-related 

My app can then remain backwards compatible without needing me to maintain separate versions and for users to do anything special when they upgrade to Django 1.9",{},{}
4827,IssuesEvent,2016-05-18 20:42:12+00:00,24529855,goldmann/docker-squash,5272931,lcarva,,,opened,Squashing not done when from_layer is None,[],[],0,"```bash
$ docker --version
Docker version 1.9.1, build ee06d03/1.9.1
$ docker pull docker.io/jboss/wildfly:latest
...
$ docker history docker.io/jboss/wildfly:latest
... 21 layers listed
$ docker-squash -t jboss/wildfly:squashed docker.io/jboss/wildfly:latest
... Squashing 21 layers
$ docker history jboss/wildfly:squashed
.. 21 layers listed
```

By providing `-f 20`, the most recent 20 layers are squashed into one resulting in a total of 2 layers, as expected. However, using `-f 21` results in no layers being squashed at all.

1. Is it possible to squash all layers into a single layer? Or is two layers the minimum?
2. This seems to have been introduced by #59 . When from_layer is None, it uses the length of layers. Maybe this should be length of layers - 1 ?

CC @twaugh",{},{}
