4877,IssuesEvent,2015-05-20 22:06:58+00:00,10102813,lepture/flask-oauthlib,1083040,hurrymaplelad,,,opened,Should `authorize_response()` check the CSRF state token?,[],[],0,"I'd like to auth with Google and protect my oauth2 callback from CSRF using the state token, but I'm not sure how I should validate the state querystring arg returned by Google to my callback.

I can do it manually with something like:
```py
def oauth2callback():
    forgery_token = session.get('ga_state', None)
    if not forgery_token or forgery_token != request.args.get('state', None):
        return make_response('Invalid state parameter.', 401)
     del session['ga_state']
    resp = google.authorized_response()
    # ...
```

But it seems oauthlib [has some plumbing for this](https://github.com/idan/oauthlib/blob/62ee76f22e8b0a53b2eda4a88e2891ed6578083b/oauthlib/oauth2/rfc6749/parameters.py#L179) in `parameters.parse_authorization_code_response`.

Any thoughts on passing state in to `authorized_response()` and plumbing it down to either [`parse_authorization_code_response`](https://github.com/idan/oauthlib/blob/62ee76f22e8b0a53b2eda4a88e2891ed6578083b/oauthlib/oauth2/rfc6749/parameters.py#L179) or through `prepare_request_body` assuming [oauthlib calls `BaseClient.prepare_token_request` instead of `parameters.prepare_token_request`](https://github.com/idan/oauthlib/issues/344)?

Seems strange to me that LinkedIn example [passes a state token](https://github.com/lepture/flask-oauthlib/blob/master/example/linkedin.py#L16) but [doesn't appear to do any of the above checks in the callback](https://github.com/lepture/flask-oauthlib/blob/master/example/linkedin.py#L47).  Am I missing something?
",{},{}
