7689,IssuesEvent,2016-03-15 20:41:52+00:00,1257514,quantmind/pulsar,144320,lsbardel,144099,quantmind,closed,"existing pid file, like test.pid prevents app from running","[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/quantmind/pulsar/labels/duplicate', 'name': 'duplicate', 'color': 'fdae6b'}]",[],0,"I discovered that pulsar decides not to start and to fail with an exist code 2 if it detects an existing pid file, even if this is a stale one.

This also happens with tests, the presence of `test.pid` file will block any further executions regardless of its content.

Any implementation of the `.pid` file pattern must check if the process exists and if it does to try to remove the file before starting. 

Current implementation is prone to failures. If you break the test executions with Ctrl-C you will not be able to run them again until you remember about the stale `test.pid`.

Sadly the same thing can be said about running pulsar in production, if the machine is restarted, even if it was configured to restart the daemon on boot, it will continue to fail because of the pid files.

Also the fact that this behaviour is not clear and that nothing is logged to the console makes the user experience even more painful.",{},{}
