8769,IssuesEvent,2016-12-09 02:30:40+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,closed,deprecation warning with Cython build_ext ,[],[],4,"When Cython is installed, the setuptools `build_ext` command tries to use `Cython.Distutils.build_ext` to build extension modules:

https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/blob/master/setuptools/command/build_ext.py#L17

With Cython 0.25, the distutils extension `Cython.Distutils.build_ext` was updated to use `cythonize` (which properly handles dependencies), and the old distutils extension deprecated and moved to `Cython.Distutils.old_build_ext`.

The change was temporarily reverted with Cython 0.25.1 to give projects time to migrate, but a deprecation warning is still printed when using Cython's `old_build_ext` as setuptools does.

```
...lib/python3.5/site-packages/Cython/Distutils/old_build_ext.py:30: UserWarning: Cython.Distutils.old_build_ext does not properly handle dependencies and is deprecated.
  ""Cython.Distutils.old_build_ext does not properly handle dependencies ""
```

I assume `setuptools.commands.build_ext` will have to be updated to import the `new_build_ext` from `Cython.Distutils.build_ext`.",{},{}
8772,IssuesEvent,2015-11-13 08:02:48+00:00,1446474,pypa/virtualenv,199657,wichert,647025,pypa,opened,Hard-linking Python binary results in weird errors on Python upgrades,[],[],0,"Our CI systems starting reporting rather bizar errors this week:

```
local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/webob/cookies.py:6: in <module>
    import hmac
/usr/lib/python2.7/hmac.py:8: in <module>
    from operator import _compare_digest as compare_digest
E   ImportError: cannot import name _compare_digest
```

This turned out to be caused by an upgrade of the system Python from 2.7.6 to 2.7.10. This upgrade changed the `operator` package. Since virtualenv uses a hardlink for the python interpreter this upgrade resulted in our virtualenvs using a Python 2.7.6 binary with the 2.7.10 stdlib. That combination does not work and resulted in the errors we were seeing.

I see two approaches to handling this:

1. use a symlink instead of a hardlink for the Python interpreter so this mismatch can not happen
2. use site.py (or a similar mechanism) to detect version changes in the Python interpreter and abort immediately, telling the user they need to re-create the virtualenv (that might require #776 to be fixed first).
",{},{}
