8929,IssuesEvent,2016-03-10 22:13:45+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,7338230,andrewkcarter,779641,Parsely,opened,Producer worker thread dies but exception never raised,[],[],0,"If the producer is setup with `block_on_queue_full=False` and the connection to the broker is lost, if the queue hits capacity the `ProducerQueueFullError` is raised causing the queue reader worker thread to terminate.

The exception is correctly assigned to the `_worker_exception` variable: https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/master/pykafka/producer.py#L494

... but `_raise_worker_exceptions()` is never called during the normal flow of producing a message when `sync=False`. The application must manually call into `producer._raise_worker_exceptions() before sending a message to detect if the producer is still actually functioning.

When the producer is configured with `sync=True`, it appears that the exception would be raised by looking at the code. But I didn't test this.

**PyKafka version**: 2.2.1
**Kafka version**: 0.9.0.0
",{},{}
8942,IssuesEvent,2016-09-27 16:10:53+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,723615,emmett9001,779641,Parsely,closed,Pykafka lost messages when exception happens,[],[],1,"Hi:

**PyKafka version**:  2.4.0
**Kafka version**:  0.9.0.0

We got some exceptions with pykafka as follow:
```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""/home/itest/scorpio_job/common/kafka/kafka_producer_client.py"", line 136, in send
    producer.produce(message)
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pykafka/producer.py"", line 341, in produce
    self._raise_worker_exceptions()
  File ""/usr/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pykafka/producer.py"", line 202, in _raise_worker_exceptions
    raise ex
error: [Errno 32] Broken pipe
```
We sended messages with async producer, so pykafka's sending thread will send more than one messages(let's say 100 messages) in a sending round. When it get ""broken pipe"" exception, this 100 messages would be lost because pykafka had remove these 100 from sending queue.
    Am I right or do I miss something?",{},{}
8944,IssuesEvent,2017-05-09 21:44:44+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,723615,emmett9001,779641,Parsely,closed,Add an upper limit to __iter__(),[],[],1,"Hello,

I wanted to see your opinion on adding an upper limit to `__iter__()`. The reason for this is because I ran into a spout problem on `streamparse/storm` where, though the Kafka Consumer could read all the messages in correctly, the spout seemingly ran into an overflow problem and eventually timed out. For example, my consumer would successfully read in 2000 messages, but the spout would hang on the `emit()` of message 1771.

My wrapping code looks like this:
```
def __iter__(self):
        counter = 0
        limit = self.limit
        while True and counter < limit:
            message = self.consumer.consume(block=True)
            if not message:
                return
            counter += 1
            yield message
```

https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/3ea3a6b585b6bd1fd8472ff3947eaa8a6fe3f962/pykafka/balancedconsumer.py#L740

-jgujgu",{},{}
8949,IssuesEvent,2016-05-12 11:42:24+00:00,19387849,Parsely/streamparse,1187034,Darkless012,779641,Parsely,opened,3.0.0.dev3: TypeError: Inputs must be ComponentSpec or GlobalStreamId objects.,[],[],0,"I'm trying to come to streamparse 3. And the most difficult part is Streams and Stream Grouping for inputs.

http://streamparse.readthedocs.io/en/master/topologies.html

There is only example of inputs with ""A dict mapping from ComponentSpec to Grouping"".
And outputs without streams.

So lets see API directly:
http://streamparse.readthedocs.io/en/master/api.html#streamparse.Bolt.spec

    inputs –
    Streams that feed into this Bolt.

    Two forms of this are acceptable:

    A dict mapping from ComponentSpec to Grouping.
    A list of Stream or ComponentSpec

Ok, so according to this the accepted inputs should be:

    inputs={my_bolt: Grouping.Grouping.fields('data')}
    or
    inputs=[my_bolt]
    
But what about streams?
Consider this example of outputs:

    outputs = [
            streamparse.Stream(fields=['data'],
                   name='unit',),
            streamparse.Stream(fields=['data'],
                   name='incident',),
        ]

So according to DOC inputs should be list of Streams?
    
    inputs=[streamparse.Stream(fields=['data'],
                   name='unit',)]

Throws an error: TypeError: Inputs must be ComponentSpec or GlobalStreamId objects.
So I guess it is not Stream that doc says, because there is no link to previous bolts (origination of data.)

So lets try:

    inputs={my_bolt : streamparse.Stream(fields=['data'],
                   name='unit',)}

KeyError: ""Invalid stream for test_bolt: 'default'. Valid streams are: ['incident', 'unit']""
So I'm guessing the defaults is taken from here:
https://github.com/Parsely/streamparse/blob/master/streamparse/dsl/component.py#L80

So How do I make Simple case scenario with Streams and grouping?

    [first_spout]         [second_spout]
        \__________ __________/
                   |
           [process_bolt]
         __________|__________
        /                     \
    [unit_bolt]          [incident_bolt]
        \__________ __________/
                   |
              [save_bolt]

",{},{}
