9341,IssuesEvent,2015-04-27 12:57:11+00:00,30921526,mozilla-services/cliquet,546692,leplatrem,1066228,mozilla-services,closed,Optimize collection timestamps in PG backend,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/mozilla-services/cliquet/labels/easy-pick', 'name': 'easy-pick', 'color': 'fbca04'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/mozilla-services/cliquet/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/mozilla-services/cliquet/labels/to%20review', 'name': 'to review', 'color': 'ededed'}]",[],1,"Currently, the current collection timestamp is obtained using a ``SELECT`` on the records and deleted tables. It is performed for each request on the resource, and those tables can be pretty huge.

In order to optimize this (*since most requests will read and not write*), is to use materialized views of postgres.

```sql
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW collection_timestamp AS (
    -- see current SELECT in python code for collection_timestamp
    ...
);
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_collection_timestamp ON collection_timestamp (user_id, resource_name);
```

In python code, we read a cached version, with a lot less records (only one per user per collection):

```sql
SELECT timestamp
   FROM collection_timestamp
   WHERE user_id = X AND resource_name = Y
```

In the ``bump_timestamp()`` SQL function, we refresh the materialized view:

```sql
REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW collection_timestamp;
```",{},{}
