11167,IssuesEvent,2015-02-13 07:57:26+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python,520669,dhermes,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,opened,PROPOSAL: Storage API consistency fix (545),"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/labels/storage', 'name': 'storage', 'color': 'bfe5bf'}]",[],0,"Guiding principles:

-   [ ] Getters and setters should **never** make HTTP requests. Lazy loading is OK,
    but only when it involves instance creation / other local (non-network bound) behavior. For [example][1], in `Bucket.acl` this already happens:

    ```python
    @property
    def acl(self):
        """"""Create our ACL on demand.""""""
        if self._acl is None:
            self._acl = BucketACL(self)
        return self._acl
    ```

-   [ ] More generally HTTP requests should be limited to explicit method calls. This also rules out constructors loading data.

-   [ ] `Blob`, `Bucket`, and `*ACL` (the only nouns) instances should have `load()`, `exists()`, `create()`, `delete()`, and `update()` methods. This design gives rise to code like

    ```python
    blob = Blob('/remote/path.txt', bucket=bucket, properties=properties)
    try:
        blob.load()  # Just metadata
    except NotFound
        blob.upload_from_file(filename)  # Sends metadata from properties
    ```

    (this maybe screams for `get_or_create()`, we'll feel it out as we develop). It's unclear if it's worth making a distinction between `storage.NOUN.update <--> PUT` and `storage.NOUN.patch <--> PATCH`. (As of right now, we don't implement `PUT` / `update` anywhere.)

-   [ ] `exists()` should use `fields` in the requests to minimize the payload.

-   [ ] A `Connection` should not be required to be bound to any object (one of the nouns `Bucket`, `ACL`, or `Blob`) but should be an optional argument to methods which actually talk to the API.

-   [ ] We should **strongly** consider adding a `last_updated` field to classes to indicate the last time the values were updated (from the server).

-   [ ] For list methods: List all buckets top-level, e.g.

    ```python
    storage.get_all_buckets(connection=optional_connection)
    ```

    and then `bucket.get_all_objects()`. It's unclear how the other 3 nouns (`objectAccessControls`, `bucketAccessControls` and `defaultObjectAccessControls`) will handle this. Right now they are handled via `ObjectACL.reload()` and `BucketACL.reload()` (a superclass of `DefaultObjectACL`).

-   [ ] Implicit behavior (default project, default bucket and/or default connection) should be used wherever possible (and documented)

@tseaver Please weigh in. This was inspired by our [discussion][2] at the end of #604.

/cc @thobrla I'd like to close #545 and focus on this (possibly broken down into sub-bugs). Does that sound OK?

[1]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/blob/f73ad7e8fc877e14e2f9c0b4ec42430f2396f770/gcloud/storage/bucket.py#L139-L144
[2]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/pull/604#issuecomment-73929760",{},{}
11180,IssuesEvent,2015-01-15 07:08:56+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python,520669,dhermes,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,closed,Decouple Transaction from Connection,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/labels/datastore', 'name': 'datastore', 'color': '0052cc'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],3,"~~After #509 is in,~~ We need to decouple `Transaction` from `Connection`  and allow `Transaction` to inherit from `Batch`.

Things to be done
-   [x] Change `Transaction` to inherit from `Batch` (#516)
-   [x] Track ""active"" batches / transactions in a thread-local stack (#518)
-   [x] Replace `Key.get()` with top-level `datastore.get()` (#520, #521, #522)
-   [x] Replace `Entity.save()` with top-level `datastore.put()` (#548)
-   [x] Replace `Key.delete()` witg top-level `datastore.delete()` (#522)
-   [x] Remove non-RPC methods `save_entity()` and `delete_entities()` from `Connection` (#550)
-   [x] Remove `Connection.mutation()`. (#550)
-   [x] Remove `Connection.transaction()` (#550)

Also relevant: #447 (`Transaction` and `Batch` should not have a `dataset_id` until they have objects to work with)

----
For reference, RPC [methods][1] are:

- Lookup
- RunQuery
- BeginTransaction
- Commit
- Rollback
- AllocateIds

[1]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-datastore/blob/21e029b2657ebb15fef5429c90c4315326855fd1/proto/datastore_v1.proto#L573",{},{}
11211,IssuesEvent,2016-12-08 23:57:24+00:00,24478117,GoogleCloudPlatform/appengine-mapreduce,419831,NickFranceschina,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,closed,are slices guaranteed to all be within the same namespace?,[],[],8,"Trying to decipher the code... but I thought I would ask anyways:  when a batch of datastore entities in a slice are sent to the map/reduce callbacks... are all of those entities in the batch guaranteed to be in the same namespace?   I ask because A) we have some code that relies on the  namespace being set before it runs... and B) we have async Operations/pool in play in our map/reduce callbacks... so it would be problematic to do, per callback, `namespace_manager.set_namespace('xxx')` and `yield PutAsync(entity)`... since by the time the actual `puts` are done by the pool, the default namespace would be indeterminate

hopefully that makes sense
",{},{}
