## Real-life consequences (anything community should be aware of, for instance how it affects your deployment)

This would disrupt self-guided learning. I identified the issue while doing a demo and found it confusing so I would imagine it's also confusing to a learner too.",{},{}
12058,IssuesEvent,2018-01-26 18:03:26+00:00,49976939,learningequality/kolibri,374612,benjaoming,3926525,learningequality,opened,"Allow KOLIBRI_HOME to include ""~""","[{'id': 492822760, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/learningequality/kolibri/labels/DEV:%20backend', 'name': 'DEV: backend', 'color': 'DFDFDF', 'default': False}, {'id': 732327197, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/learningequality/kolibri/labels/DEV:%20distributions', 'name': 'DEV: distributions', 'color': 'dfdfdf', 'default': False}, {'id': 703587154, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/learningequality/kolibri/labels/TAG:%20beginner%20issue', 'name': 'TAG: beginner issue', 'color': 'c1e23b', 'default': False}]",[],0,"### Observed behavior

A user or deployment specialist should be able to specify `~` in `KOLIBRI_HOME`. This fails.

### Expected behavior

That the currently logged in user's home is resolved and used. We used use `os.path.expanduser`

### User-facing consequences

Possibly minor, but anyone would be in their right mind to think that `~/` is valid.

### Errors and logs

```
