12414,IssuesEvent,2017-10-03 07:50:12+00:00,12968651,pgmpy/pgmpy,18470647,lohani2280,5500131,pgmpy,opened, No need of using `defaultdict` for implementing `get_cardinality` method of various models.,[],[],0,"###
I think a normal dict would also suffice this implementation.Its because, defaultdict is similar to the usual dictionary (dict) container, but it has one difference: that it is initialized with a function that takes no arguments and provides the default value for a nonexistent key. Thus , a defaultdict will never raise a KeyError if you try to get an item with a key that is not currently in the dictionary unlike usual dict container.
Now ,here in this method we are always appending variables and its corresponding cardinality into the dict container.We are never retrieving a value using a key(either an existing or non-existing key). So ,if their is no retrieval then a normal dict would itself suffice .
",{},{}
12438,IssuesEvent,2018-01-24 12:39:51+00:00,12968651,pgmpy/pgmpy,8164573,rodolfolottin,5500131,pgmpy,closed,Recalculating CPDs of Bayesian Model,[],[],3,"In softwares like Netika or Hugin, on running mode, if you change the CPDs of a node, the changes propagate to the others connected nodes modifying its parameters. I am making some manual tests just changing the cpd node values, but they dont propagate to the others. Like:

`
model.get_cpds()[0].values[1][0] += 0.01
`
`
model.get_cpds()[0].values[1][1] -= 0.01
`

Is there a way to do it using the Inference classes?",{},{}
