14876,IssuesEvent,2016-01-17 03:19:53+00:00,23292534,Calysto/metakernel,3029504,bsvh,9684179,Calysto,opened,metakernel won't work on unix systems without bash,[],[],0,"I tried using the octave_kernel on an OpenBSD system that does not have bash installed, but it fails because of Metakernel. I was able to fix this easily by changing to `def bash(command=""sh"", prompt_regex=re.compile('[$#]'))` of replwrap.py, and `pexpect.which('sh')` in shell_magics.py, since it doesn't seem like anything you are using bash for in this case is bash-specific. However, I'm not sure whether it affects the MetaKernel Bash or not.",{},{}
14886,IssuesEvent,2016-04-10 22:03:10+00:00,31589410,chainreactionmfg/mutablerecords,14081283,grybmadsci,9809398,chainreactionmfg,opened,Records can't be pickled because of the Metaclass used to create them.,[],[],0,"I've got a mostly-working fix for this, but the loaded record doesn't compare equal to the dumped record because a new type with the same name gets created (obviously).  I'd like to propose a change to the equality check for `RecordClass` so that it more closely matches the equality check of `namedtuple`s.  `namedtuple` instances compare equal if corresponding fields (by index, not name), compare equal, essentially as if they were normal tuples.  I'd like to propose an update to the equality check of `RecordClass` to one of:
 - Records are equal iff all required fields compare equal (compared according to index, not name) and all optional fields compare equal, compared according to name (basically dicts mapping optional field name to value compare equal).  This most closely matches `namedtuple`, but does allow you to do weird things.
 - Same as previous, but compare all fields by name, rather than comparing required fields positionally.
 - Same as previous, but also require that the Record type names match.

Thoughts?  Any of these work for my purposes, I think the last on is a little too strict of a check, but only because of how loose `namedtuple` comparisons are.",{},{}
14894,IssuesEvent,2017-12-06 16:09:27+00:00,26876372,dateutil/dateutil,1377457,pganssle,9849410,dateutil,closed,Explicitly drop support for python setup.py test,"[{'id': 149492528, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/help%20wanted', 'name': 'help wanted', 'color': '159818', 'default': True}, {'id': 667039516, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/low-difficulty', 'name': 'low-difficulty', 'color': '0e8a16', 'default': False}, {'id': 335791870, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dateutil/dateutil/labels/tests', 'name': 'tests', 'color': '5319e7', 'default': False}]",[],2,"We recently have switched to using `pytest` (or `tox`) as the test runner, in favor of `setup.py test`. I don't know if there's a good reason *not* to use `setup.py test` integration with `pytest`. If someone is interested in taking this issue, [here is the pytest page on setup.py integration](https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/goodpractices.html#integrating-with-setuptools-python-setup-py-test-pytest-runner).",{},{}
