15620,IssuesEvent,2017-05-04 22:28:24+00:00,55713112,quodlibet/mutagen,1668979,mmcco,11544695,quodlibet,opened,Inconsistent command line option syntax,[],[],0,"All of the long-form options such as `--delete-frames` and `--picture` take an equals sign between its option and argument (e.g. `--delete-frames=TORY`). However, the options used to set frames don't, and they will silently include the equals sign in the tag itself. For example, `mid3v2 --TORY=1993 foo.mp3` will set the `TORY` frame to `=1993`. One can easily overlook this when using `mid3v2 -l foo.mp3`, too.

I can think of two possible solutions:

1. Strip the equals sign if the argument isn't quoted. This is a slight change in behavior, but there are extremely few cases in which someone would start a field value with an equals sign.
2. Print a warning to stderr when an argument matches this pattern.

Thanks for your time,
Mike",{},{}
15653,IssuesEvent,2016-09-18 22:33:39+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,3085284,NikolajBjorner,11668813,Z3Prover,closed,Z3 does not terminate on a simple problem,[],[],1,"If I execute Z3 on the following problem, it terminates and says ""sat"":

```
(declare-sort B 0)
(declare-sort W 0)

(declare-fun mnot (B) B)
(declare-fun mand (B B) B)

(declare-fun T (B W) Bool)

(assert (forall ((w W) (p B)) 
  (iff (T (mnot p) w) 
       (not (T p w))   )
))

(check-sat)
```

However, if I execute Z3 on the following slightly different problem (with one additional assertion), Z3 seems to loop forever:

```
(declare-sort B 0)
(declare-sort W 0)

(declare-fun mnot (B) B)
(declare-fun mand (B B) B)

(declare-fun T (B W) Bool)

(assert (forall ((w W) (p B)) 
  (iff (T (mnot p) w) 
       (not (T p w))   )
))

(assert (forall ((w W) (p B) (q B)) 
  (iff (T (mand p q) w) 
       (and (T p w) (T q w)) )
))

(check-sat)
```

The second problem does not seem to be much harder than the first problem, and I know that it is satisfiable too. I wonder why Z3 cannot terminate and find a model for the second problem.  I hope that this simple example may help to improve Z3's model search.

(By the way, I haven't tried, but I suspect that Isabelle's Nitpick would be able to find a model.)
",{},{}
