17213,IssuesEvent,2016-03-10 09:54:08+00:00,1553944,wireservice/csvkit,8162529,KarolTx,17111824,wireservice,opened,csvstat: output in CSV format,[],[],0,"Hi, could the csvstat command be extended to output the stats in CSV-like format:?

```
column,class,count,nulls,unique,min,max,sum,mean,median,stdev,max_length,fv_1,fv_2,fv_3,fv_4,fv_5
AAA,int,1000,23,4,...
```

It would help a lot on data discovery. Thank you for the great tool.
Cheers,
Karol
",{},{}
17215,IssuesEvent,2017-01-02 20:12:54+00:00,1553944,wireservice/csvkit,26463,jpmckinney,17111824,wireservice,closed,Add option to in2csv to list sheet names,"[{'id': 91206, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/wireservice/csvkit/labels/feature', 'name': 'feature', 'color': '02e10c', 'default': False}, {'id': 52750573, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/wireservice/csvkit/labels/Normal%20Priority', 'name': 'Normal Priority', 'color': 'fef2c0', 'default': False}]",[],1,"When converting multi-sheet excel spreadsheets to CSV, the `--sheet` option for `in2csv` is needed.

Currently, I don't believe there is any way to _list_ the sheets in the document without viewing it in something external like Excel or LibreOffice.

Would it be possible to add an option to list all available sheets? It may even be worth making this the default behavior for in2csv when multiple sheets are present and no specific sheet is specified -- this way a user doesn't accidentally grab the first sheet without realizing there are others.
",{},{}
17219,IssuesEvent,2016-06-21 19:45:14+00:00,1553944,wireservice/csvkit,153008,solidsnack,17111824,wireservice,opened,Allow `-H` to relabel headers,[],[],0,"Consider data sources that generate CSV without headers -- this might be due to chunking or something similar in a processing pipeline.

With `-H` as it stands we can use this data but the resulting query code is confusing. If `-H` or a related argument accepted a comma separated list of new column names, it would alleviate the confusion thus resulting.

A penny for your thoughts.",{},{}
17225,IssuesEvent,2017-04-15 15:57:08+00:00,1553944,wireservice/csvkit,26463,jpmckinney,17111824,wireservice,closed,Create a documentation on how to install git version of csvkit,"[{'id': 91208, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/wireservice/csvkit/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': '02d7e1', 'default': False}, {'id': 52750592, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/wireservice/csvkit/labels/Low%20Priority', 'name': 'Low Priority', 'color': 'c7def8', 'default': False}]",[],4,"Due to many changes to csvkit and, in parallel, to dependencies (like agate), it is not easy to make a working installation out of git checkout.

I suggest to add a portion of docs to ""Tips and troubleshooting"" considering the installation of csvkit and relatives from git, using virtualenv and either `pip install git+<repourl>` or `git clone <repourl>; pip install -r <reqfile>`. Plus, adding the link to such a doc from README to allow for people visiting Github repo to quickly jump on working on the library.",{},{}
