17249,IssuesEvent,2017-06-21 12:27:42+00:00,51442999,python-cmd2/cmd2,2812720,tleonhardt,17161025,python-cmd2,closed,Abbreviations of multiline commands do not accept multiple lines,"[{'id': 324131050, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/python-cmd2/cmd2/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': True}, {'id': 554473465, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/python-cmd2/cmd2/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': '5319e7', 'default': False}, {'id': 324131055, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/python-cmd2/cmd2/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c', 'default': True}]",[],10,"After adding a command to Cmd.multilineCommands, only the full name of the command accepts multiple lines. Abbreviations of the command still work, but only accept a single line.

Example:
```python
import sys
from cmd2 import Cmd

class MLApp(Cmd):
    Cmd.multilineCommands.append('foobar')
    
    def do_foobar(self, line):
        print('foobar')

    def do_wassup(self, line):
        print('wassup')

def main():
    app = MLApp()
    app.cmdloop()

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
```

The output:
```
pi@raspi:~ $ python3 ~/ml_abbrev.py
(Cmd) was
wassup
(Cmd) wassup
wassup
(Cmd) foo
foobar
(Cmd) foobar
> one
> two
> ;
foobar
(Cmd)
```
",{},{}
17255,IssuesEvent,2018-02-19 13:43:34+00:00,51442999,python-cmd2/cmd2,2812720,tleonhardt,17161025,python-cmd2,opened,Update remove_unused.py example,[],[],0,"Now that the functionality present in ``do_cmdenvironment`` got combined with ``do_set``, the [remove_unused.py](https://github.com/python-cmd2/cmd2/blob/master/examples/remove_unused.py) example is outdated and needs to be updated.",{},{}
17261,IssuesEvent,2017-09-22 12:33:13+00:00,51442999,python-cmd2/cmd2,6162585,sluser,17161025,python-cmd2,opened,Issue with # character in command strings,[],[],0,"Hello,
I recently upgraded my application from 0.6.7 to 0.7.7. This went smoothly with one exception. One one of my cmd2 application's test cases calls a command with a parameter including a '#' character. Previously, this worked fine, but with the new version, the test failed. I found that actually, any time a # appears in the command string, the # and all characters following it are stripped off. This is a change in behaviour.

I did have a quick look into the cmd2 source, and the obvious suspicious area is comment stripping. The question is, was the change in behaviour caused by a new bug, or a bug fix?

If it is the latter, it would be good to have way to disable this behaviour, as I have a need to have # characters in commands but do not need to support comments.

Unfortunately, I cannot share the application in question, but to illustrate the issue:

`Client: call command(arg=""abc#def"")

*** invalid syntax - 'call command (arg=""abc ***

Client: call co#mmand(arg=""abcdef"")

*** invalid syntax - 'call co ***`

I verified that the truncated string is indeed what gets sent to my command class, i.e. it is being truncated before it reaches my application code.
",{},{}
17269,IssuesEvent,2017-11-01 10:14:52+00:00,17420614,seleniumbase/SeleniumBase,6418226,dickcarlee,17287301,seleniumbase,opened,Xpath selector in BaseCase.functions,[],[],0,"Hi @mdmintz , it's a perfect package!
I have met a question about BaseCase.functions, in most of functions, you check if the way of 'By'  is 'page_utils.is_xpath_selector()' and that convenient, but this step isn't cover all of the functions, e.g: 'BaseCase.get_text()',
` def get_text(self, selector, by=By.CSS_SELECTOR,
                 timeout=settings.SMALL_TIMEOUT):`
        `if self.timeout_multiplier and timeout == settings.SMALL_TIMEOUT:`
            `timeout = self._get_new_timeout(timeout)`
       `self.wait_for_ready_state_complete()`
        `time.sleep(0.01)`
        `element = page_actions.wait_for_element_visible(  self.driver, selector, by, timeout)` 
that's a little bit annoying.
",{},{}
