17413,IssuesEvent,2017-08-08 21:23:23+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,649860,SwartzCr,17889013,certbot,closed,Explain authentication requirements,"[{'id': 245387015, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/area:%20documentation', 'name': 'area: documentation', 'color': 'c5def5', 'default': False}, {'id': 276680181, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/more-info', 'name': 'more-info', 'color': '006b75', 'default': False}]",[],7,"Debian 9

ii  certbot                                0.10.2-1                       all          automatically configure HTTPS using Let's Encrypt
ii  python-certbot                         0.10.2-1                       all          main library for certbot


## I ran this command and it produced this output:
```
# certbot certonly
Saving debug log to /var/log/letsencrypt/letsencrypt.log

How would you like to authenticate with the ACME CA?
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1: Place files in webroot directory (webroot)
2: Spin up a temporary webserver (standalone)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Select the appropriate number [1-2] then [enter] (press 'c' to cancel): 
```

## Certbot's behavior differed from what I expected because:

It's unclear what both of the choices do and require. Standalone sounds good, but I think it requires port 80 and/or 443 to be free, which they probably aren't as those are common ports for existing web servers. ;)
Webroot sounds OK, but does this root need to be accessible via port 80 or via port 443?

What if port 80 redirects all requests to https?
What if port 80 isn't used at all?

I think:
1. This scenario should be supported better.
2. Things should be explained better.",{},{}
17420,IssuesEvent,2017-01-20 17:40:38+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,6504915,bmw,17889013,certbot,closed,apt-get install with -qq on certbot-auto --quiet,"[{'id': 276243379, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/certbot-auto', 'name': 'certbot-auto', 'color': '00a080', 'default': False}, {'id': 146954789, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 281347824, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/has%20pr', 'name': 'has pr', 'color': '0052cc', 'default': False}]",[],0,"hello everybody,

on a call of certbot-auto on a freshly installed linux box, certbot-auto attempt to install some packages like python and others via apt-get.

if certbot-auto was called with --quiet however, apt-get firstly does not respect the quiet parameter. furthermore a confirmation to install the packages (""y"" + enter) is necessary, potentially blocking an automated system (installation) completely.

i beg of a maintainer to add ""-qq"" to any possible apt-get if certbot-auto was called with the ""--quiet"" parameter.

thank you very much for your attention.
",{},{}
