",{},{}
17446,IssuesEvent,2016-07-20 00:18:00+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,6504915,bmw,17889013,certbot,opened,Apache default default,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/apache', 'name': 'apache', 'color': 'fbca04'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/ui%20/%20ux', 'name': 'ui / ux', 'color': '5319e7'}]",[],0,"So in `certbot_apache/constants.py` we have this code:
```
    os_info = util.get_os_info()
    try:
        constants = CLI_DEFAULTS[os_info[0].lower()]
    except KeyError:
        constants = CLI_DEFAULTS[""debian""]
```
Basically, if you're OS isn't one we we expect, we assume it's Debian. Is this the correct behavior? With Debian, we assume there are `sites-available`/`sites-enabled`, `mods-available`/`mods-enabled`/, `a2enmod`/`a2dismod`, etc.

Perhaps if we can't recognize your OS, we should choose defaults with `handle_mods` and `handle_sites` set to `False` by default. I created this issue in response to #3302.

@joohoi, IIRC you wrote most of this code. What do you think?",{},{}
17450,IssuesEvent,2018-05-03 19:41:50+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,1813285,sydneyli,17889013,certbot,opened,Port sender-only TLS configuration as a Postfix plugin enhancement,"[{'id': 838715693, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/area:%20postfix', 'name': 'area: postfix', 'color': '0f16e0', 'default': False}, {'id': 291660454, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/certbot/certbot/labels/area:%20security%20enhancements', 'name': 'area: security enhancements', 'color': 'c5def5', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'sydneyli', 'id': 1813285, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars3.githubusercontent.com/u/1813285?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/sydneyli', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/sydneyli/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"@bmw and I discussed this offline, the gist of which was:
There should be an easy way for someone to set recommended SMTP configurations for a sending-only server, including the `starttls-policy` enhancement.

This is a little bit odd for `deploy_cert` to do since a sender doesn't need a certificate. Solely using `starttls-policy` to create a Postfix-compatible `tls_policy_maps` file isn't completely sufficient, either, since we'd like to help configure users' TLS setting correctly as well.",{},{}
